Introduction to fplr

fplr-intro.Rmd

This vignette is an introduction to the principles and functions of the fplr package.

1. Basics

What is Fantasy Premier League?

Fantasy Premier League (FPL) is the official fantasy football game of the Premier League, the top competitive football division in England. FPL players compete to score the most points come the end of the season (following these rules).

What is fplr?

fplr is an R package that provides a set of tools for working with FPL data in R. It contains functions for interfacing with FPL user (referred to herein as “users”) and player (referred to herein as “players”) data, in both current and previous seasons of the game.

N.B. The package retrieves this data from the FPL site (specifically bootstrap-static JSON). At time of writing, there is no formal developer support, and so any sudden game alterations that affect the data structure may cause functionality in this package to break.

2. Players

Functions in the player data family primarily return information about players in the game, and are mostly for exploring data in the current season (note - when a new season of the game begins, data from these functions will be overwritten).

Current FPL season

  • fpl_get_players: Aggregate (season-level) data for players in the current FPL season
fpl_get_players()

3. Users

Functions in the user data family primarily return information about FPL users, and like players, are mostly for exploring data in the current season (note - when a new season of the game begins, data from these functions are overwritten).

Current FPL season

  • fpl_get_user_performance: User performance data for the current FPL season
